e-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Herzberg's main work concerned atomic and molecular <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Spectroscopy\" title=\"Spectroscopy\">spectroscopy<\/a>. He is well known for using these techniques that determine the structures of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Diatomic\" title=\"Diatomic\" class=\"mw-redirect\">diatomic<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Polyatomic\" title=\"Polyatomic\" class=\"mw-redirect\">polyatomic<\/a> molecules, including <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Free_radicals\" title=\"Free radicals\" class=\"mw-redirect\">free radicals<\/a> which are difficult to investigate in any other way, and for the chemical analysis of astronomical objects. Herzberg served as Chancellor of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Carleton_University\" title=\"Carleton University\">Carleton University<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ottawa\" title=\"Ottawa\">Ottawa<\/a>, Canada from 1973 to 1980.<\/p>","name":"Gerhard Herzberg","place_of_birth":"Hamburg ,  Germany","place_of_death":"Ottawa ,  Ontario","text":"Gerhard Herzberg ,  born in Germany , Chemistry, 1971","year":1971.0}